{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c4a6eefc-925d-48bf-86e8-d98474ab68f6","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** (most likely):\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips`. Recent crashes appear here within seconds.\n\n2. **Core dumps** (if enabled):\n   ```bash\n   # Check/enable core dumps:\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   # Cores go to /cores/core.<pid>\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n   macOS disables core dumps by default and SIP may block them.\n\n3. **Console.app** — open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for a formatted view of the `.ips` files.\n\n**Tip:** The `.ips` crash report contains the faulting thread, stack trace, and signal info — often enough to diagnose the issue without a full core dump.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e2fb321c-631e-4086-8090-42e5c6f288e7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":284,"requestId":"418E:36C261:64A2B0E:6DD56D9:69F1632F"},"id":"1aab7acd-0707-4cd8-815a-c67b57b4882e","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:47:37.744Z","parentId":"8d100813-4044-42fc-b860-909155493fdf"}
